## 3. The clean structural finding (σ1 = 1.000, σ2 = -3.322)

The pre-registered "sanity check" was: σ1 should be ≈ 1 for simple zeros by calculus linearization. Result:

| Function | σ1 α (mean ± std across 5 zeros) | σ2 α |
|---|---|---|
| ζ(½+it) | 1.000 ± 0.000 | -3.322 ± 0.000 |
| J₀(x) | 1.000 ± 0.000 | -3.322 ± 0.000 |
| Ai(x) | 1.000 ± 0.000 | -3.321 ± 0.000 |

This is **identically 1.000 to four decimal places** across all 15 zeros. The float64 evaluation of these three functions near their respective zeros is consistent with the local linearization to within regression precision.

σ2's value of -3.322 matches -log₂(10) ≈ -3.3219 — the algebraic conversion between log₁₀(|δ|) and log₂(|f|). This is the structural relation predicted in P_B2.

**Interpretation:** At the linearization order in float64, the simple-zero blow-up signature is structural and universal. It carries no fixture-discriminating information. Anyone fitting log|f| vs log|δ| near a simple zero of any function will get α ≈ 1.

## 4. σ3 trivially universal — the oracle-vs-float64 ratio collapsed

σ3 was defined as log₁₀(|f_oracle| / |f_float64|). The result was α₃ = 0 ± 0 for every function and every zero. Interpretation: across the swept δ range (10⁻¹ to 10⁻¹⁰), the float64 evaluation of ζ, J₀, Ai is **indistinguishable from the mpmath-50 high-precision oracle to within the regression's noise floor**. The ratio is exactly 1.0 at every measurement point.

This is itself a finding (mpmath/scipy float64 evaluation is faithful for these zeros at the δ scales tested) but it means σ3 has zero discriminative power. Phase ε would need to push δ smaller (down to 10⁻¹⁵+) where the float64 ULP floor kicks in to surface a non-trivial oracle/float64 divergence.

## 5. σ4 — the route-permutation degeneracy in route definitions

Route-B definitions per function:

| Function | Route B (intended) | Route B (actual) | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| ζ | ζ(1-s̄)* via functional equation | Mathematically equivalent to ζ(s) on the critical line (where s = ½+it, 1-s = ½-it = s̄, so ζ(1-s̄)* = ζ(s)*conjugate* = ζ(s)) | Degenerate — Route B = Route A exactly |
| J₀ | J₀(-x) by evenness | J₀(-x) = J₀(x) mathematically and in float64 | Degenerate — Route B = Route A exactly |
| Ai | Hybrid: Ai(x-ε) + Bi(x+ε)·ε | **Not actually a re-evaluation of Ai** — it's a finite-difference-like hybrid involving Bi | Computes a clean -1 power law, but doesn't measure pure-Ai route variation |

The σ4 = -1.005 for Airy is a **real measurement of the hybrid's behavior**, just not of *pure-Ai route variation*. The clean α = -1.005 ± 0.005 across all 5 Ai zeros, with r² > 0.999, indicates a structural property: the hybrid expression `Ai(x-ε) + Bi(x+ε)·ε` differs from Ai(x) by a quantity that grows as 1/|δ| in ULP units near a zero of Ai. This is consistent with the linearization: near zero, |Ai(x)| ≈ |Ai'(zero)|·|δ|, so ulp(|Ai|) ≈ |δ|·const; the hybrid difference is ~ const, hence ratio ~ 1/|δ|.

**This is a substrate observation about Ai's neighborhood — not pure-Ai route variation as P_B4 intended.** Honest disclosure of the methodology limitation.

Phase ε fix: implement genuinely-different float64 evaluation routes for each function. For ζ, use the Euler-Maclaurin series (large-t expansion) as route B; for J₀, use the asymptotic series for large x; for Ai, use the integral representation or asymptotic expansion. These would produce algebraically-different float64 chains for the same mathematical function.

## 6. σ5 observability boundary — no data

The pre-registered heuristic was "the largest δ at which float64 value < 10⁻¹⁵." Across the swept δ ∈ [10⁻¹⁰, 10⁻¹], no record's float64 value fell below 10⁻¹⁵. The smallest measured |f| was ~|f'|·10⁻¹⁰ ≈ 10⁻¹⁰ for J₀/Ai zeros (where |f'| is O(1)), well above the threshold.

P_B5 fails for lack of measurement, not for a substantive finding. To observe the ULP floor, the sweep needs to extend to δ ∈ [10⁻¹⁵, 10⁻¹³]. Phase ε scope.

